oakcurric:unit-3855
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Remote learning: games making"@en ;
  curric:slug "home-learning-games-making" ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit will explore basic agility, balance and coordination skills with a focus
  on ball control and challenges to develop competence in a range of games. Pupils will need
  to think creatively to modify the ideas presented to them whilst producing personal best
  performances."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Pupils will already have experienced simple target games and understand
  basic principles of attack and defence. They will explore ways to control and manipulate a
  ball with their hands and/or feet, whilst setting increasing complex challenges to accomplish
  and also design games that provide an immersive experience to practice their ball handling
  skills.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3855-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3855-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3855-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3855-4 ;
  curric:id "3855"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:23.884634Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-physical-education-key-stage-3 .

oakcurric:unit-3856
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Remote learning: moving with confidence"@en ;
  curric:slug "home-learning-moving-with-confidence" ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit will support the development of quality movement by focusing on form,
  body control and foundational movement skills such as agility, balance and coordination.
  Pupils will be challenged to accurately replicate an increasingly complex variety of
  movements with control and fluency."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Pupils will already have experienced basic movement tasks to include
  exploring how to balance, rotate and safe ways to land. Pupils will now refine their
  technique and body awareness to execute more challenging skills and build more complex
  sequences of movement.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3856-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3856-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3856-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3856-4 ;
  curric:id "3856"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:23.901578Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-physical-education-key-stage-3 .

oakcurric:unit-3857
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Remote learning: dance development"@en ;
  curric:slug "home-learning-dance-development" ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit focuses upon personal experiences to consolidate and deepen pupil
  knowledge and understanding of Action-Space-Dynamics-Relationships to create, develop and
  analyse ideas, motifs and dances. Pupils will use similarities and differences to form
  connections and contrast."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Throughout KS1 and KS2, pupils have had the opportunity to choreograph
  dance sequences in character, demonstrating musicality, emotion and creativity, aligned to
  multiple stimuli. This unit will take the next step into developing pupils' knowledge and
  application of specific dance steps and challenge pupils to focus on the aesthetics of their
  performance. Pupils will be required to utilise their current knowledge and understanding
  around choreography in order to create and perform complex dance sequences, using specific
  dance steps alongside accurate timing.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3857-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3857-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3857-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3857-4 ;
  curric:id "3857"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:23.913839Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-physical-education-key-stage-3 .

oakcurric:unit-3859
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Remote learning:  health and fitness"@en ;
  curric:slug "home-learning-health-and-fitness" ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit explores correct bodyweight techniques and training for strength, power,
  endurance, flexibility, balance and coordination. Pupils learn to adapt exercises, stay
  safe and understand the physical, mental and social benefits of activity."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Pupils will already have experienced elements of fitness training and have
  improved their understanding of how the body responds to exercise. Later in health and
  wellbeing, pupils will learn more about setting SMART targets to help motivate and review
  progress.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3859-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3859-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3859-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3859-4 ;
  curric:id "3859"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:23.932495Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-physical-education-key-stage-3 .

oakcurric:unit-3858
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Remote learning: outdoor adventure activities"@en ;
  curric:slug "home-learning-outdoor-adventure-activities" ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit will enhance pupils' ability to respond effectively to physical
  challenges and problems. A key focus will be on developing planning and strategic thinking
  by requiring pupils to methodically solve problems under time constraints. Pupils will
  develop critical reflection skills."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Pupils will already have developed basic skills to operate as a team but
  this unit challenges pupils to apply them in unique scenarios that require problem solving
  and creative thinking. Later in outdoor adventurous activities, pupils will get the
  opportunity to engage in activities beyond the school walls which will further develop their
  teamwork and leadership skills.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3858-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3858-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3858-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3858-4 ;
  curric:id "3858"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:23.954972Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-physical-education-key-stage-3 .

oakcurric:unit-3026
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Dance: identity"@en ;
  curric:slug "dance-identity" ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit is a thematic approach drawing upon personal experiences to consolidate
  and deepen their knowledge and understanding of Action-Space-Dynamics-Relationships to
  create, develop and analyse ideas, motifs and dances. They will use similarities and
  differences to form connections and contrast."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Throughout KS1 and 2, pupils have had the opportunity to choreograph dance
  sequences in character, demonstrating musicality, emotion and creativity, aligned to multiple
  stimuli. This unit will take the next step into developing pupils' knowledge and application
  of specific dance steps and challenge pupils to focus on the aesthetics of their performance
  as opposed to characterisation. Pupils will be required to utilise all of their knowledge and
  understanding around choreography, to create and perform complex dance sequences using
  specific dance steps with accurate timings.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3026-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3026-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3026-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3026-4 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3026-5 ;
  curric:id "3026"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:24.953605Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-physical-education-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-move-movement-competence ,
    oakcurric:thread-feel-engagement-and-enjoyment .

oakcurric:unit-3046
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Invasion games: adapt tactics and strategies through handball"@en ;
  curric:slug "invasion-games-adapt-tactics-and-strategies-through-handball" ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit explores ways to adapt skills, tactics and strategies and apply them
  with adherence to the rules of handball. Pupils will develop their resilience as they
  utilise the full rules and officiate their own games."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Pupils will already have adapted a wider range of tactics and strategies
  in a range of scenarios and specific sports like football, netball and rugby. This unit takes
  that understanding into the context of handball with a focus on resilience by using scenario
  cards for pupils to respond to in games. Later in invasion games they will apply a variety of
  tactics and strategies in AFL, hockey and korfball.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3046-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3046-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3046-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3046-4 ;
  curric:id "3046"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:24.985813Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-physical-education-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-move-application-of-tactics-strategies-and-compositional-ideas ,
    oakcurric:thread-think-knowledge-of-rules-tactics-strategies-and-compositional-ideas .

oakcurric:unit-3042
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Invasion games: adapt tactics and strategies through Gaelic football"@en ;
  curric:slug "invasion-games-adapt-tactics-and-strategies-through-gaelic-football" ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit explores ways to adapt skills, tactics and strategies from football,
  rugby and handball to Gaelic football. Pupils will learn how to transfer skills of running
  with the ball, kicking and tackling plus new skills like fisting and soloing as they
  experience a game that will be new to most."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Pupils will already have developed their skills in contact and explored a
  wider range of tactics and strategies in a range of scenarios and specific sports like
  football, netball and rugby. This unit takes that understanding into the context of Gaelic
  football to enable pupils to experience a new game and transfer the relevant skills whilst
  learning a new set of rules. Later in invasion games they will apply tactics and strategies
  via games with different rules like handball, AFL and hockey.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3042-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3042-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3042-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3042-4 ;
  curric:id "3042"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:24.988159Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-physical-education-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-move-application-of-tactics-strategies-and-compositional-ideas ,
    oakcurric:thread-feel-engagement-and-enjoyment .

oakcurric:unit-3023
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Gymnastics: body control and paired sequences"@en ;
  curric:slug "gymnastics-body-control-and-paired-sequences" ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit will explore core gymnastics skills both individually and in
  combination. Pupils will develop their stability whilst holding their own body position
  and when supporting a partner. They will learn how to give appropriate feedback to others
  on posture and the execution of short sequences."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Pupils will already have experienced basic ideas in gymnastics to include
  exploring how to balance, roll, rotate and safe ways to land from apparatus including a
  bench. Pupils will now refine their technique and body awareness to execute more challenging
  skills and build more complex sequences in pairs. Later in gymnastics they will become more
  technically fluent and able to analyse group performances.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3023-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3023-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3023-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3023-4 ;
  curric:id "3023"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:24.990879Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-physical-education-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-move-movement-competence ,
    oakcurric:thread-feel-personal-and-emotional .

oakcurric:unit-3033
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Health and wellbeing: long term benefits of physical activity through circuits"@en ;
  curric:slug "health-and-wellbeing-long-term-benefits-of-physical-activity-through-circuits" ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit will explore the correct technique for body weight exercises along with
  an understanding of how to adapt and modify stations to ensure a training benefit. Pupils
  will learn about the physical, mental and social benefits of physical activity and how to
  ensure they are safe when training."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Pupils will already have experienced elements of fitness training and have
  improved their understanding of how the body responds to exercise through OAA: teamwork,
  fitness and movement skills in action as well as athletics: run, throw, jump and officiate.
  Later in health and wellbeing pupils will learn more about leadership and setting SMART
  targets to help motivate and review progress.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3033-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3033-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3033-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3033-4 ;
  curric:id "3033"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:25.110077Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-physical-education-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-move-physical-fitness ,
    oakcurric:thread-think-knowledge-of-healthy-active-living .

oakcurric:unit-3037
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Dance: crossing continents"@en ;
  curric:slug "dance-crossing-continents" ;
  rdfs:comment """The unit explores a stylistic approach that outlines the different application of
  Action-Space-Dynamics-Relationships to four contrasting but inter-related dance styles
  enabling the learners to draw comparisons and consider why and how wider societal factors
  affected their evolution."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit develops pupils understanding of how we can learn about a
  society through the arts and how they reflect and affect the norms and accepted culture of
  their time. Pupils will be introduced to how the dance styles studied spread in terms of
  their geographic reach as well shifting between fulfilling a social function into an art
  form. This unit builds upon the work in the ‘Everyday Art’ unit, appreciating the purposes of
  art. Pupils will refine their sense of aesthetics, accuracy of placement and be able to
  identify key stylistic qualities.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3037-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3037-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3037-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3037-4 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3037-5 ;
  curric:id "3037"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:25.112291Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-physical-education-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-move-movement-competence ,
    oakcurric:thread-connect-cultural-and-ethical-awareness .

oakcurric:unit-3040
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Athletics: train and perform in a sport education season"@en ;
  curric:slug "athletics-train-and-perform-in-a-sport-education-season" ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit will develop pupils’ ability to perform in a range of athletic events
  with a focus on personal best improvements. They will learn about different components of
  fitness and the difference between aerobic and anaerobic exercise. Pupils will take
  responsibility for working in small teams."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Pupils will already have developed the necessary core techniques for
  different running, jumping and throwing events. After they train to improve different aspects
  of fitness, pupils will contribute towards the performance of their team as they grow in
  confidence and challenge themselves to improve further. Later in athletics pupils will focus
  on pace or power whilst demonstrating increasing independence.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3040-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3040-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3040-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3040-4 ;
  curric:id "3040"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:25.184697Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-physical-education-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-move-physical-fitness ,
    oakcurric:thread-think-knowledge-of-healthy-active-living .

oakcurric:unit-3030
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Inclusive sports: teamship, communication and awareness of others"@en ;
  curric:slug "inclusive-sports-teamship-communication-and-awareness-of-others" ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit explores how to measure success beyond the outcomes of competition, how
  to balance competition, and how to ensure games are inclusive, respectful, supportive and
  engaging for all. Pupils will develop their teamship skills through improved
  communication, empathy and awareness of others."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Pupils will already have developed their foundational movement skills and
  ability to apply tactics to overcome opponents in a variety of invasion games. Being able to
  work with others in a respectful, kind and compassionate way is an important skill and forms
  the focus of this unit through a variety of contexts that help raise awareness. Later pupils
  will be expected to apply these skills in a broad range of games and other activities.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3030-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3030-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3030-3 ;
  curric:id "3030"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:25.186681Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-physical-education-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-move-application-of-tactics-strategies-and-compositional-ideas ,
    oakcurric:thread-connect-cultural-and-ethical-awareness .

oakcurric:unit-3032
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Invasion games: tactics and strategies to outwit opponents through football"@en ;
  curric:slug "invasion-games-tactics-and-strategies-to-outwit-opponents-through-football" ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit will apply a wider range of tactics and strategies through football.
  Increasingly complex approaches to attack and strategies to defend will be applied whilst
  enhancing knowledge of the rules and tactics specific to football. Pupils will also work
  on their organisational skills."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Pupils will already have explored a wider range of tactics and strategies
  to include dispersal, penetration, support and screening in attack whilst defensive
  strategies of delay, compactness, depth, balance and control/ restraint in ‘donor’ sports and
  scenarios but also through futsal so now they can apply these to the specific sport of
  football. Later in invasion games and other competitions they will explore ways to outwit,
  using advanced tactics and strategies, full-contact sports like rugby.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3032-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3032-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3032-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3032-4 ;
  curric:id "3032"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:25.188596Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-physical-education-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-think-knowledge-of-rules-tactics-strategies-and-compositional-ideas ,
    oakcurric:thread-move-performance-and-competition .

oakcurric:unit-3028
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Athletics: run, jump, throw and officiate"@en ;
  curric:slug "athletics-run-jump-throw-and-officiate" ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit will explore core techniques and use knowledge to become more
  technically proficient at sprinting, jogging and a range of both jumping and throwing
  events. Pupils will learn how the body responds to different types of exercise, how to be
  self-motivated and how to officiate fairly."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Pupils will already have experienced a range of athletics events and have
  some awareness of the differences between sprinting fast and pacing yourself for running
  longer distances. They will have experimented with jumping for height, jumping for distance
  and ways to throw different implements such as tennis balls, quoits and foam/ vortex
  javelins. Later in athletics they will train and refine skills further whilst also learning
  to operate as a mini-team through a sport education season.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3028-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3028-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3028-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3028-4 ;
  curric:id "3028"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:25.286826Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-physical-education-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-move-movement-competence ,
    oakcurric:thread-think-knowledge-of-healthy-active-living .

oakcurric:unit-3045
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Health and wellbeing: healthy leadership and effective reviewing skills"@en ;
  curric:slug "health-and-wellbeing-healthy-leadership-and-effective-reviewing-skills" ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit will explore ways to lead, motivate and set SMART targets for themselves
  and others to help construct a meaningful fitness based activity. Pupils will also learn
  about some of the barriers to participation and how to review progress to help maintain
  motivation."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Pupils will already have developed their technique and understanding
  around body weight exercises and how to adjust a circuit training routine to maximise long
  term health and fitness benefits. They will combine this with ideas around effective
  leadership in a range of contexts. Later in health and wellbeing pupils will commit to a
  personalised fitness and learn more about nutrition, energy and the importance of hydration
  on physical and mental health.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3045-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3045-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3045-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3045-4 ;
  curric:id "3045"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:25.290106Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-physical-education-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-move-physical-fitness ,
    oakcurric:thread-think-knowledge-of-healthy-active-living ,
    oakcurric:thread-connect-teamwork-and-leadership .

oakcurric:unit-3035
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Net and wall games: technical proficiency and problem solving through badminton"@en ;
  curric:slug "net-and-wall-games-technical-proficiency-and-problem-solving-through-badminton" ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit will apply hand-eye coordination and racket skills to badminton with a
  focus on problem solving to win points and increasing proficiency with serves, clears and
  smashes. Pupils will also develop their ability to analyse performances to identify
  strengths and weaknesses."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Pupils will already have explored basic skills to hit forehands and
  backhands and ideas for maintaining rallies in pickleball. This unit requires pupils to
  transfer these skills and basic tactics to badminton where every shot is hit without a
  bounce. They will need to accurately replicate key techniques whilst also figuring out how to
  outwit their opposition. Later in net and wall games they will understand more about
  effective performance and further develop their decision making skills.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3035-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3035-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3035-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3035-4 ;
  curric:id "3035"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:25.294100Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-physical-education-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-think-decision-making-problem-solving-and-creative-thinking ,
    oakcurric:thread-move-performance-and-competition .

oakcurric:unit-3020
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Outdoor adventurous activities: teamwork, fitness and movement skills"@en ;
  curric:slug "outdoor-adventurous-activities-teamwork-fitness-and-movement-skills" ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit explores skillful movement and physical fitness through teamwork
  challenges. Pupils will develop teamwork skills and understand both why and how to warm up
  for different types of physical activity."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """At primary school, pupils are introduced to basic outdoor and adventurous
  activities (OAA), teamwork, and fitness challenges. This unit at the start of secondary
  school levels the playing field for those with less exposure to competitive sports and helps
  everyone feel they belong in PE. The OAA elements help pupils get familiar with their new
  environment and teamwork challenges encourage mixing beyond immediate friends. Later, pupils
  will face more complex physical and intellectual challenges in OAA.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3020-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3020-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3020-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3020-4 ;
  curric:id "3020"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:25.296305Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-physical-education-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-move-physical-fitness ,
    oakcurric:thread-connect-teamwork-and-leadership .

oakcurric:unit-3044
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Parkour: control, confidence and creativity"@en ;
  curric:slug "parkour-control-confidence-and-creativity" ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit will explore parkour with a focus on safety, fun and gradual skill
  development. Pupils will build their confidence and creativity tackling increasingly
  complex movements to include landing, rolling and precision jumps utilising a range of
  equipment and apparatus."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Pupils will already have used a variety of apparatus and covered the basic
  movements used for flight and safe landings. They will already be able to set up apparatus
  safely and recognise the importance of practising within their limits. Later in gymnastics
  they will apply these skills in trampolining with a focus on aesthetic appreciation and
  linking controlled movements.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3044-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3044-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3044-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3044-4 ;
  curric:id "3044"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:25.323873Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-physical-education-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-move-movement-competence ,
    oakcurric:thread-feel-personal-and-emotional .

oakcurric:unit-3041
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Invasion games: adapt tactics and strategies in contact sports"@en ;
  curric:slug "invasion-games-adapt-tactics-and-strategies-in-contact-sports" ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit explores ways to adapt tactics and strategies in full-contact sports
  like rugby. Pupils will learn how to respond to specific types of breakdown such as free
  kicks, rucks, mauls and scrums as they seek solutions to gain territory, maintain momentum
  and counterattack."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Pupils will already have explored a wider range of tactics and strategies
  to include dispersal, penetration, support and screening in attack whilst defensive
  strategies of delay, compactness, depth, balance and control/ restraint will have been
  applied in a range of scenarios and specific sports like football, netball and rugby. This
  unit takes that understanding into a variety of full-contact situations that require great
  teamwork and the confidence to engage in tackles/ full body contact. Pupils will also learn
  about sporting values and fair play, which is developed in many future units.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3041-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3041-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3041-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3041-4 ;
  curric:id "3041"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:25.325899Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-physical-education-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-move-application-of-tactics-strategies-and-compositional-ideas ,
    oakcurric:thread-feel-personal-and-emotional .

oakcurric:unit-3025
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Invasion games: basic tactics to overcome opponents through netball"@en ;
  curric:slug "invasion-games-basic-tactics-to-overcome-opponents-through-netball" ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit will build on fundamental skills and apply tactics to overcome opponents
  through netball. Development of basic passing, receiving, footwork, dodging, shooting, and
  defending skills with positivity in small sided games. Pupils will learn the rules of
  netball and names of major bones."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Pupils will already have explored principles of keeping possession of a
  ball either in hand or at feet in ‘donor’ sports and scenarios (core tasks). Pupils will now
  apply that learning to pass accurately and move off the ball to create space and options to
  outwit others in netball. They will improve their quality of movement to avoid breaking the
  footwork rule and also refine skills to accurately replicate the shooting technique via
  reciprocal learning. Later in invasion games they will experience basketball.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3025-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3025-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3025-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3025-4 ;
  curric:id "3025"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:25.371945Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-physical-education-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-think-decision-making-problem-solving-and-creative-thinking ,
    oakcurric:thread-move-performance-and-competition .

oakcurric:unit-3039
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Striking and fielding games: competition and performance analysis in cricket"@en ;
  curric:slug "striking-and-fielding-games-competition-and-performance-analysis-in-cricket" ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit will develop techniques for batting in cricket whilst bringing in
  statistical analysis to help with decision making. Fielding skills will be refined before
  overarm bowling is refined to enable games of pairs cricket."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Pupils will already have explored the core skills of batting, bowling and
  fielding in an attempt to score or deny runs. The drive and pull shots will enable pupils to
  place the ball in different areas of the field before testing confidence, mental capacity and
  appetite for risk through small sided scoring and officiating games. Later in striking and
  fielding games pupils will play and officiate their own small sided team games of cricket and
  continue to develop their ability to analyse performances.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3039-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3039-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3039-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3039-4 ;
  curric:id "3039"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:25.481990Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-physical-education-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-think-evaluation-analysis-and-reflection ,
    oakcurric:thread-move-performance-and-competition .

oakcurric:unit-3027
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Striking and fielding games: bowling, batting and fielding with accuracy"@en ;
  curric:slug "striking-and-fielding-games-bowling-batting-and-fielding-with-accuracy" ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit will develop core skills in batting, bowling and fielding with the
  intention of outwitting opponents. Pupils will learn to play simple games with a variety
  of equipment to ensure success and be given quality practice time to focus on accuracy in
  games like rounders."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Pupils will already have explored basic skills of batting and running to
  score as well as bowling and fielding to deny scoring opportunities through an introduction
  to rounders and cricket. Pupils will now refine these skills to improve accuracy and become
  increasingly aware of the impact of misfielding. Later in striking and fielding games pupils
  will apply principles to cricket and learn to compete and to analyse performance to suggest
  ways to improve.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3027-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3027-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3027-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3027-4 ;
  curric:id "3027"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:25.484623Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-physical-education-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-move-movement-competence ,
    oakcurric:thread-feel-engagement-and-enjoyment .

oakcurric:unit-3024
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Net and wall games: maintain and win a rally through pickleball"@en ;
  curric:slug "net-and-wall-games-maintain-and-win-a-rally-through-pickleball" ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit will explore basic skills to start, maintain and win a rally in racket
  sports. Pupils will learn the specific rules to pickleball and develop persistence when
  improving racket skills to play in pairs. They will also work on observation skills to
  officiate and improve performance."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Pupils will already have explored basic bat and ball (net/ wall) games at
  primary school. This requires pupils to transfer and apply previously learnt principles of
  attack and defence to consider how they apply in a different context. They will need to
  persist with tasks set and develop their ability to observe others to officiate and/ or
  coach. Later in net and wall games they will develop basic skills and hand-eye coordination
  further whilst also learning specific rules and techniques for badminton and tennis.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3024-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3024-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3024-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3024-4 ;
  curric:id "3024"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:25.523700Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-physical-education-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-connect-teamwork-and-leadership ,
    oakcurric:thread-move-performance-and-competition .

oakcurric:unit-3022
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Invasion games: basic tactics to overcome opponents through futsal"@en ;
  curric:slug "invasion-games-basic-tactics-to-overcome-opponents-through-futsal" ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit will build on fundamental skills and apply tactics to overcome opponents
  through futsal. Development of basic ball control, passing, shooting, dribbling, marking
  and tackling skills with determination in small sided games. Pupils will learn the rules
  of futsal and names of major muscles."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Pupils will already have explored principles of keeping possession of a
  ball either in hand or at feet in ‘donor’ sports and scenarios (core tasks). Pupils will now
  apply that learning to move on and off the ball to create space, to create options and to
  outwit others in futsal. The heavier ball lends itself to small sided games, increased
  control and keeping the ball on the floor to support less experienced pupils and level the
  playing field. Later in invasion games they will also apply these principles to netball.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3022-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3022-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3022-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3022-4 ;
  curric:id "3022"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:25.531375Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-physical-education-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-move-movement-competence ,
    oakcurric:thread-think-knowledge-of-rules-tactics-strategies-and-compositional-ideas .

oakcurric:unit-3031
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Invasion games: tactics and strategies to outwit opponents in donor sports"@en ;
  curric:slug "invasion-games-tactics-and-strategies-to-outwit-opponents-in-donor-sports" ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit explores a wider range of tactics and strategies to include dispersal,
  penetration, support and screening in attack whilst defensive strategies of delay,
  compactness, depth, balance and control/ restraint can be applied in many sports with the
  ball in hand, at feet or on a stick."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Pupils will already have explored tactics to overcome opponents with a
  focus on keeping possession of a ball either in hand or at your feet. Pupils will have learnt
  how to move on and off the ball to create space, to create options and to outwit others in
  ‘donor’ sports and scenarios but also through transferring and applying these skills in
  specific sports like futsal and netball. They will increasingly show the emotional
  intelligence to work well with their peers. Later in invasion games they will apply these
  tactics and strategies in games like football and rugby.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3031-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3031-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3031-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3031-4 ;
  curric:id "3031"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:25.533495Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-physical-education-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-think-decision-making-problem-solving-and-creative-thinking ,
    oakcurric:thread-move-application-of-tactics-strategies-and-compositional-ideas .

oakcurric:unit-3036
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Invasion games: tactics and strategies to outwit through rugby"@en ;
  curric:slug "invasion-games-tactics-and-strategies-to-outwit-through-rugby" ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit will develop knowledge of the rules and apply a wider range of tactics
  and strategies through rugby. Pupils will apply attacking and defensive strategies with
  creativity and careful consideration of safety."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Pupils will already have explored a wider range of tactics and strategies
  to include dispersal, penetration, support and screening in attack whilst defensive
  strategies of delay, compactness, depth, balance and control/ restraint in ‘donor’ sports and
  scenarios but also through football so now they can transfer these (where appropriate) to the
  specific sport of rugby. Later in invasion games they will explore more ways to outwit in
  full-contact sports.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3036-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3036-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3036-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3036-4 ;
